my_fn <- function(data, mapping, ...){
  p <- ggplot(data = data, mapping = mapping) + 
    geom_point(pch=19,alpha=0.5,color='blue') + 
    geom_smooth(method=lm, fill="red", color="red", se=FALSE, ...) +
    theme_bw()
  p
}
g = ggpairs(ames_train,columns = c(3,7,53,20,22), lower = list(continuous = my_fn))
g

  1. Suppose you are examining the relationship between price and area. Which of the following variable transformations makes the relationship appear to be the most linear?
    1. Do not transform either price or area
    2. Log-transform price but not area
    3. Log-transform area but not price
    4. Log-transform both price and area 
# type your code for Question 5 here, and Knit
ggplot(ames_train,aes(x=log(area),y=log(price)))+geom_point(pch=19,color='blue',alpha=0.5)+geom_smooth(method=lm,color='red',se=F)+theme_bw()+labs(x="Area",y="Price")

cor(ames_train$area,ames_train$price)
## [1] 0.7127375
cor(log(ames_train$area),log(ames_train$price))
## [1] 0.7393174
cor(log(ames_train$area),ames_train$price)
## [1] 0.7006098
cor(ames_train$area,log(ames_train$price))
## [1] 0.714812
# When both price and area are log transformed the correlation is the greatest.
